observations.recommendation:
The Municipal Accountant stop the practice of recording the purchase of inventories as outright expenses and use the inventory method of accounting as prescribed in the Manual of the NGAS and IPSAS 12;

Municipal Accountant reconcile the affected accounts and prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the balances reflected in the financial statements; and

Municipal Accountant and the GSO Head prepare supply ledger cards and stock cards, respectively, and to reconcile both records regularly.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

1. Obtain all source documents from the source agencies to review the terms and conditions corresponding to the funds transferred in relation to the implementation of programs and projects;


2. Determine if the specific programs or projects for which the funds were transferred were implemented, goods/services were delivered, liquidation of funds were already submitted and received by the source agencies, and the liabilities were settled for proper adjustments in the books;

3. Return to the source agency any unused/unexpended balance; and


4. Request authority for the write off of dormant fund transfer accounts in accordance with COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require: 

a. The Municipal Social and Development Officer together with the Property Supply Officer to conduct physical count of all the unissued donated items;


b. Prepare inventory list of the unissued donated items for DRRM every month or until all donations are fully distributed;


c. Henceforth, prepare a Report on the Receipt and Distribution/Issuance of Donated Relief Goods and Report on the Receipt and Utilization/Issuance of Donated PPE to account and monitor the receipt and issuances of all donations in kind and submit a copy of all the reports to the Audit Team;

d. The Municipal Supply Officer to furnish the Municipal Accountant with the duplicate copies of all Acknowledgement Receipts of in-kind donations and inventory list of donated items for DRRM; and


e. The Municipal Accountant to summarize data from the documents submitted by the Municipal Social and Development Officer and Supply Officer, compare records with the Registry of Donated Relief Goods for DRRM maintained by the Municipal Social and Development Officer for check and balance, and disclose the necessary information in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended the Municipal Accountant to:

a.	Record the unrecorded deposit/balance of the three bank accounts namely the: (a) Municipality of San Francisco GF (LBP), (b) Municipality of San Francisco Trust Fund (DBP) and (c)San Francisco Municipality – PHIC Professional Fee amounting to P448,484.61, P173,607.97 and P19,300.00, respectively, as confirmed by the bank as at December 31, 2024; 

b.	Obtain bank statements and prepare bank reconciliation statement of the San Francisco Trust Fund Account with account number 3322-1128-90 to account for the difference amounting to P810,346.66;



c.	Request supporting documents relative to the unrecorded book reconciling items and untraced prior years’ adjustments aggregating P1,527,376.48 and reconcile the differences between the balances between the bank confirmation replies and the amount recorded in the books amounting to P1,799,589.10 by preparing bank reconciliation statements and record the book reconciling items, if warranted. 

We recommended the Municipal Treasurer to process immediately the reactivation of the dormant account, Municipality of San Francisco GF with account number 0942-1007-52 or cause closure of the same, if not reactivated and transfer the balance to an active account to protect the amount from loss of rights and ownership and to avoid dormancy fee.

We recommended the GSIS Employee-in-Charge to:

a.	Exert best efforts to reconcile with the GSIS the records and information of all active employees in Calendar Year 2024 such as monthly salaries to update the exact premium amounts to be withheld/recorded and remitted for the personal share and government share and account for the difference amounting to P380,449.62 and P397,827.11 as presented in Tables 11 and 12, respectively;


Submit List of Active Employees to the GSIS and request for the deletion of inactive employees showing the underpayment amounting to P230,219.02 as presented in Table 16 as of December 31, 2024;



c.	Reconcile the records and information of the all employees with underpayment as per records of the GSIS amounting to P613,178.11 as presented in Table 15 and make adjusting entries to recognize the underpayment, if necessary. Once reconciled, settle the underpayments to avoid incurring interests;

d.	Reconcile the differences in the loan amortization as reflected in the GSIS billing, the amount recorded and withheld and amount remitted aggregating P180,234.47 and P134,580.74, as presented in Tables 17 and 18, respectively;

e.	Henceforth, conduct regular/periodic reconciliation of the premium amounts and loan amortizations to be withheld and remitted with the records of the GSIS to avoid underpaid/overpaid premium amounts and loan amortizations. The reconciliation of the GSIS accounts of the employees is not a daily activity and not even a year-round activity.

We also recommended the Municipal Accountant to exhaust all possible means and continue to exert utmost effort to account for the beginning balance of the Due to the GSIS account amounting to P427,358.32 and make adjusting entries, if necessary.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor to direct the Municipal Accountant to:

a.	Correct the erroneous recording of the withholding tax in January by making the necessary adjusting entry in the ledger;

b.	In coordination with the Municipal Treasurer, review and reconcile the discrepancies in the withholding and remittance of the Documentary Stamp Tax for CY 2024;

c.	Reconcile the beginning balance recorded in the General Ledger of the Due to BIR account for withholding of taxes with the actual amount remitted to trace the amount of over-remittance, and make the necessary adjustments.  Henceforth, conduct regular reconciliation of the balances; and

d.	Strictly remit the taxes withheld within the period prescribed under the Revenue Regulations and ensure that balances of the month must be remitted on the following month.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to:

a.	Require the concerned Revenue Collection Clerks to submit justification on the late remittance of collections amounting to P 24,191.77 as presented in Table 23 and henceforth, require them to remit to the Municipal Treasurer the full amount of their collections on a daily basis as required by COA Circular No. 92-382;



b.	Require the concerned Revenue Collection Clerks to indicate the date of remittance of their collections to the Liquidating Officer amounting to P32,247.30 as presented in Table 24;



c.	Require the Liquidating Officer to indicate the date of receipt of collections and remittances from the Revenue Collection Clerks and the date of verification of the said collections amounting to P157,173.76 as presented in Table 24;




d.	Require the Municipal Treasurer to account for the unaccounted differences of collections vis-à-vis deposit in January and February 2024 amounting to P185,442.96 and P26,183.80, respectively as presented in Table 25;





e.	Require the Municipal Treasurer and the Revenue Clerks that the official receipts be written in hard indelible ballpen and the duplicate and triplicate copies will be clear carbon reproductions in all respects of whatever may have been written on the original.

