We recommended that the Management:
Direct the concerned personnel to prepare the required summary list together with the required supporting documents and reports on cash donations and in-kind and submit the same to COA;
Post the reports on the receipt and utilization of DRRMF sourced from GAA and donations in cash and in-kind in the LGU website;
Instruct the GSO to coordinate with the MSWDO and Mayor’s Office with regards to the donated items to be able to maintain inventory list thereof; and
Strictly adhere to COA Circular Nos. 2014-002 and 2020-009 on the accounting and reporting guidelines of cash and in-kind donations.

We recommended that the Management:
Instruct the Municipal Engineer to submit the list of on-going PPAs and those projects to be implemented and require all contractors to install project billboards on site containing complete and updated information;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to require attachment of photos of the installed billboards at the project site upon payment of Mobilization Costs or First Progress billing. Also, collect the cost of materials and labor under pay item project billboards from all contractors for the uninstalled project billboards;
Strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2013-004 for timely verification of the PPAs’ status and validation of projects/programs/activities signboards and/or public notices and on the information and publicity on Programs/Projects/Activities of government agencies as well as the provisions of law on full public disclosure policy.

We reiterated our previous recommendation that the Management:
Issue a demand letter to all accountable officers for the immediate liquidation/ settlement of their unliquidated cash advances and in case of non-compliance, withhold from their salaries the total amount due for said concerned officials and employees;
Ensure that all cash advances are fully liquidated as soon as the purpose of the cash advance has been served; and
Strictly adhere with the rules & regulations on granting and liquidation of cash advance pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-002 and Section 89 of PD 1445;

We recommended the following:
The Inventory Committee shall conduct a physical inventory of the all local road network under the LGU’s jurisdiction and reconcile the local road inventory with the records of the accounting office;
The Municipal GSO must maintain the Local Road Inventory and Road Map and to keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for each road network;
The Municipal Engineer shall provide the local accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for all its local road networks with the help of the Municipal Assessor on the assessment of road lot component;
The Municipal Accountant shall ensure that all local road networks and its component will be recorded in the book of accounts.

We recommended that the Management:
Refrain from disbursing funds not appropriated for training expenses or representation expenses and provide additional budget for said expenses in the future budgets;
Inform the Office of the Auditor in all its activities before the said activity will be undertaken;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant that payments of catering services should be supported with Inspection and Acceptance Report and Narrative Report or Minutes of the Meeting and meticulously examine its supporting documents; and
The principle of judicious utilization of government funds as emphasized in Section 2 of PD 1445 must be considered at all times.

We recommended that the management instruct the BAC and its Secretariat:
To be sensitive on its calendar activities in the conduct of its procurement process;
To require all winning bidders to submit construction safety and health program duly approved by the DOLE;
To see to it that dates in the receipt of NOA and NTP by the successful bidder; and
To strictly adhere with pertinent provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184.

We recommended that the management direct the concerned official to:
Make constant follow up for the needed spare part so that Solid Waste Processing Machineries can operate already;
Monitor the prioritization of the establishment of MRF by allocating fund for its construction and the constructed MRF of every barangay, the facility must be designed to accommodate efficiently and store recyclable wastes before transferring to disposal facility or sanitary landfill;
Closely monitor the proper segregation of solid waste disposal by every household and establishments collected at the Materials Recovery Facilities as temporary dumpsite, and impose sanctions/penalties for every household and establishments which violated the proper segregation of solid waste in coordination with the Barangay Officials;
Impose sanctions to the Barangays who failed to comply the requirements of RA 9003 at their level; and
Continue to mobilize the active participation of schools, private organization and barangay officials informing, educating and monitoring households in the proper waste disposal from source.

1.6	We recommended and the following municipal officials and employees agreed that:
1.6.1	The Mayor create a plantilla or designate a GSO/property custodian who will be in-charged in monitoring the receipt, safekeeping and disposition of the procured supplies and properties of the LGU;
1.6.2	The designated Inventory and Disposal Committee Team Leader to initiate the planning and conduct periodic physical inventory of ALL the supplies and property of the LGU as mandated in Section 124 of the NGAS Manual.  Prepare and submit also the RPCI as a result of the inventory taking of the supplies.  The RPCPPE and RPCI shall be reconciled with the property custodian and accounting records.  These Reports shall also be submitted to COA pursuant to Section 124 of NGAS Manual for LGU;
1.6.3	The Inventory and Disposal Committee Team Leader to ensure that all supplies in the RPCI and PPEs in the RPCPPE should contain complete information/identification, like item description, date acquired, serial numbers, property tags, cost, etc.  These data would be helpful in identifying and comparing the properties between records;
1.6.4	The Property Custodian to make and maintain a list of all the supplies and property of the LGU, with complete information thereof reflected therein.  The list shall be reconciled with the similar records in the accounting at least a quarter;
1.6.5	The Municipal Accountant to maintain Supplies, PPEs and other property Ledger Cards, as well as complete list/schedule of the same.  Again, the supplies and property in the list/schedule should bear complete information as to description and specification.  Reconcile the accounting records with the list/reports being kept by the Property Custodian or with the Inventory and Disposal Committee at least quarterly. Exert more effort to substantiate items with unreconciled balances;
1.6.6	The Property Custodian to property tag every PPE.  This will help in easy and fast monitoring of the assets and identification thereof in case a loss of the same.  Moreover, fast track the disposition of the unserviceable motor vehicles.  Property without cost must be appraised by in-house appraiser or an independent appraiser or from the province;
1.6.7	The Property Custodian to provide PAR to every PPE issued to respective end users.  Accountability to the property redounds to the latter; and
1.6.8	The Management to adhere to Sections 119, 120 and 124 of the NGAS Manual, Volume 1, Section 3(c), Chapter   V   of   the   Manual   on   Property Custodianship, paragraph 13 of IPSAS No. 17, and other pertinent laws, rules and regulations governing the conduct of physical count of properties, maintenance of records and submission of reports thereof to the Auditor.

We recommended that the Management:
Issue a demand letter to all accountable officers for the immediate liquidation/ settlement of their unliquidated cash advances and in case of non-compliance, withhold from their salaries the total amount due for those who are still active and find any legal remedies to compel the liquidation of cash advances for those who are not already connected with the LGU;
Ensure that all cash advances are fully liquidated as soon as the purpose of the cash advance has been served;
Make necessary actions for the proper reporting of dormant accounts by submitting request for write-off of dormant accounts and its underlying supporting documents to prove that the accounts are no longer collectible.

We recommended that the management instruct the BAC and its Secretariat:
To include the copy of the posting of the NOA and NTP in the PhilGEPS when they submit contracts and bidding documents;
To require all winning bidders to submit construction safety and health program duly approved by the DOLE;
To intensify the conduct of post qualification so that only qualified contractors will be awarded with contracts; and
To strictly adhere with pertinent provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184.

We recommended that Management:
Stop charging ineligible expenses to 5% LDRRMF;
Allocate additional funds for regular operation expenses of the LDRRM Office;
Instruct the MDRRMO to consider the timing in the purchase of perishable goods; and
Follow strictly the regulation in the utilization of the 5% Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund as provided under Section 5.1 of the Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1 of DBM and DILG dated March 25, 2013.
It is also recommended that purchases of goods and supplies in bulk should be recorded to its proper inventory account upon purchase and eventually recorded to its proper expense account upon consummation or distribution. Further, accountable officer is also required to prepare a Monthly Report of Supplies and Materials Issued (MRSMI) and submit the said report, together with the copy of distribution list properly received by the beneficiaries, to the Accounting Office for recording purposes in the books of accounts.

We recommend that the Local Chief Executive to:

a.) take into consideration to relieve the disbursing officer from her current duties and responsibilities to prevent from the occurrence of a more pervasive effect without prejudice to existing laws and regulations and to assign a new AO;

b.) require the Municipal Treasurer to implement a sound cash management including the close supervision of the employees under his custody;

c.) require the Municipal Accountant to issue demand letters to those accountable officers with outstanding cash advances; and

d.) improve the payroll system of the Municipality and take into consideration the shifting from the usual payroll system to an electronic (ATM) one.

